## Diagnosis

The two-axis grammar (color channel via `border`, weight channel via `ring` on engaged) is architecturally correct, but the resting state is being rendered at `2px` because either:

1. Tailwind 4's default `border` utility emits `border-width: 2px` (if the CSS variable `--default-border-width` was overridden in the theme), **or**
2. The component is applying `ring-2` / `border-2` unconditionally in the base class rather than only on the engaged variant, **or**
3. The design token for the border width axis was set to `2` across both states during the previous fix session.

The engaged `ring` overlay is correct — it's a paint-only zero-layout-impact layer. The error is solely that the resting border weight is `2px` instead of `1px`.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Conflated state tokens:** a single weight value is being shared across resting and engaged states instead of being independently tokenized per state. The previous fix correctly split *color* onto two axes but left *weight* as a single value applied globally.

---

## Fix

### 1. Design tokens — `src/styles/tokens/components/input.css`

```css
/* src/styles/tokens/components/input.css */
@layer elan.tokens {
  :root {
    /* Border weight axis */
    --input-border-width-rest:     1px;   /* hairline — was 2px ← BUG */
    --input-border-width-engaged:  2px;   /* ring overlay only        */

    /* Border color axis */
    --input-border-color-rest:     var(--color-neutral-300);
    --input-border-color-focus:    var(--color-brand-500);
    --input-border-color-error:    var(--color-error-500);
    --input-border-color-disabled: var(--color-neutral-200);
  }
}
```

---

### 2. Component — `src/components/elan/Input/Input.tsx`

```tsx
// src/components/elan/Input/Input.tsx

const inputBase = [
  // Layout
  "w-full rounded-md px-3 py-2 text-sm",
  // Background
  "bg-surface-input",
  // ── Color channel: always-present 1 px border ──────────────────
  // Uses the token directly; Tailwind sees a literal class, no purge risk.
  "border border-[color:var(--input-border-color-rest)]",
  // Transitions
  "transition-[border-color,box-shadow] duration-150 ease-out",
  // Reset browser outline — we own the engaged signal via ring
  "outline-none",
].join(" ");

const inputVariants = cva(inputBase, {
  variants: {
    state: {
      // ── Weight channel: paint-only ring added on focus ──────────
      // ring-offset-0 keeps it flush; ring draws outside border-box
      // so layout is undisturbed.
      default: [
        "border-[color:var(--input-border-color-rest)]",
        "focus-visible:ring-2",
        "focus-visible:ring-[color:var(--input-border-color-focus)]",
        "focus-visible:ring-offset-0",
        "focus-visible:border-[color:var(--input-border-color-focus)]",
      ].join(" "),

      error: [
        "border-[color:var(--input-border-color-error)]",
        "focus-visible:ring-2",
        "focus-visible:ring-[color:var(--input-border-color-error)]",
        "focus-visible:ring-offset-0",
      ].join(" "),

      disabled: [
        "border-[color:var(--input-border-color-disabled)]",
        "cursor-not-allowed opacity-50",
      ].join(" "),
    },
  },
  defaultVariants: { state: "default" },
});
```

> **Why `border` (not `border-2`) in `inputBase`?**
> Tailwind 4's `border` utility without a numeric suffix resolves to `border-width: 1px`. `border-2` is `2px`. The previous session's fix accidentally promoted the class to `border-2` or set the CSS variable to `2`. We revert to the bare `border` class.

---

### 3. Global reset guard — `src/styles/globals.css`

Ensure Tailwind 4's preflight isn't being overridden to default all borders to `2px`:

```css
/* src/styles/globals.css */
@layer base {
  *,
  ::before,
  ::after {
    /* Explicit reset — prevents any upstream preflight drift */
    border-width: 0;
    border-style: solid;
    border-color: var(--color-neutral-300);
  }
}
```

This guarantees `border` (without a suffix) means exactly `1px solid` with no interference.

---

### 4. Visual regression test — `src/components/elan/Input/Input.test.tsx`

Pin both states so this doesn't regress a fifth time:

```tsx
// src/components/elan/Input/Input.test.tsx
import { render } from "@testing-library/react";
import { Input } from "./Input";

describe("Input border weight axis", () => {
  it("resting: border-width is 1px (hairline)", () => {
    const { getByRole } = render(<Input placeholder="test" />);
    const el = getByRole("textbox");
    const styles = getComputedStyle(el);
    expect(styles.borderWidth).toBe("1px");   // ← must be 1, not 2
  });

  it("engaged: ring class present, base border unchanged", () => {
    const { getByRole } = render(<Input placeholder="test" />);
    const el = getByRole("textbox");
    // ring-2 is applied via focus-visible — class must be declared
    expect(el.className).toMatch(/focus-visible:ring-2/);
    // Base border class must be bare `border`, never `border-2`
    expect(el.className).not.toMatch(/\bborder-2\b/);
  });
});
```

---

## Principle

**Two-axis input affordance grammar:**

| Axis | Resting | Engaged |
|---|---|---|
| Color channel (`border-color`) | `neutral-300` | `brand-500` / `error-500` |
| Weight channel (`ring`) | absent | `ring-2` (paint-only, zero layout impact) |
| Border width | `1px` always | `1px` always (ring provides the visual bump) |

The border width is **invariant at 1px across all states**. The engaged state's apparent "thickening" is entirely the ring overlay — not a change to `border-width`. Never couple the weight axis to `border-width`; that causes layout shift and is the class of error that produced this bug (AP-072).
